My aunt lived in that area, and we were taken there daily. I can remember her telling me I was special and that I would be a star someday. That I had to do everything she said. Listen, practice.
My father was supposed to be watching my sister and me, but he would take us there and leave us with her. For part of that time we stayed with my aunt until we could get our own place. My father was supposed to be looking for work, but he would take off with my blood uncles every day, so it got to be that I never saw either parent for long periods of time. That would change on occasion when my father would take me with him to bars while he drank or played in a band or both. I would be at the bar with one of his girlfriends. It seemed perfectly natural to me.
My aunt began to sexually abuse me the first night. It continued the entire time we were there. Months. I didn't know until years later that my sister was locked in a closet while this went on.
Eventually we got a place of our own and the abuse stopped.
A few months later my cousins came to live with us and the sexual abuse started again. Just different people. It ended a few months later when they were caught. They had us tied up. The cords were tight. Not really cords at all, cloths line. My sister and I were tied back to back. My cousins, a sister and brother had already molested us for over an hour. I cannot recall where my mother was during that period of my life. She was gone a lot. I think she was working because he didn't work. That's all I know.

Listen to Anna, a survivor of teen dating violence. She‚Äôs courageously telling us what we need to hear, not only during Teen Dating Awareness Month #TDVAM, as @thefeministparent explains in her latest reel (check it out).

As a freshman, Anna was ‚Äúinstantly hooked‚Äù by a varsity athlete who made her feel great‚Äîuntil he didn‚Äôt. Read her @womensmediacenter story via our highlights or linktree.

Anna wants people to learn the warning signs of teen dating and how to get help. She recommends @sashclubs ‚ÄúTeen Dating Violence‚Äù Power Topic presentation, via our Power Topics highlight or linktree.

Like many survivors of abuse by male athletes, she found it pointless to report because the school ignored victims. If Anna‚Äôs school had supported reporting students, she could have avoided years of trauma. Schools must create a safe environment for all students, take reports compassionately, and act quickly to stop the harassment. Too often schools don‚Äôt--so students are denied their right to an education free from sexual harassment as guaranteed by Title IX, a federal civil rights law.

Use @ssaisorg toolkits (in our highlights) to ensure your school is taking the required steps to protect students.

‚ú® Setting and respecting boundaries is vital in any relationship so that all partners feel safe communicating their needs without fear of retaliation. Healthy relationships involve comfortable dialogues around wants, goals, fears, and limits, with the understanding that everyone's expressed boundaries will be honored. Boundaries can come in many different forms: 

üß† Emotional: Trust and comfort are essential in a healthy relationship that partners build over time by demonstrating reliability.

‚úã Physical: Partners know how far the other wants to go based on open communication. Your boundaries should always reflect how ready you feel personally.

üíª Digital: You and your partner should feel able to discuss your needs and wants. Remember: changes to the terms should be made together with respect.

üóØÔ∏è Conflict: Conflict is normal, but your arguments shouldn‚Äôt turn into personal attacks. If you can‚Äôt express yourself without fear of retaliation, you may be experiencing abuse.

Follow @loveisrespectofficial and visit ‚û°Ô∏è https://www.loveisrespect.org/everyone-deserves-a-healthy-relationship/how-to-set-boundaries/ for more information on setting boundaries for a healthy relationship.

Trigger warning - unpopular opinion...

As a psychologist, wellness coach, and human being, I often feel like the world/society is moving in the exact opposite direction than what I'm doing and what my worldview is.

From the #metoo movement, to #democracy, from #healthcare in general to #conspiracytheory and so many more topics... I have a fundamentalky different opinion than the overall concesus seems to be.

I feel the world/society has gotten ridiculous! We've gone absolutely mad as a species. And yes, that is my professional opinion.

I see so many people being confused about their basic identity, people being overly sensitive and expecting everyone around them to take their specific preferences and possible triggers into account (which, by the way are different for each individual AND not the world's responsibility), doctors having no clue about actual health care, people being offered the option to get euthanized simply because main stream therapists don't have the holistic knowledge and experience to treat people properly. We're being co-erced and gaslit into taking experimental shots, with no liability of the manufacturers. We're being led to believe that there is a climate crisis that can be stopped by cutting off our food supply (farmers) and replace it with artifial meat and such, while formula 1 continues.

I mean, come on! 

Your health, your triggers, your decisions, healing from trauma, finding the right therapists and doctors for YOU, creating safety... is YOUR responsibility. No one else's. It's time to take your power back!! Because the world  needs you happy, healthy, and thriving, not constantly in survival mode from trying to fit into a profoundly sick society. The world needs your contribution, not your whining. The world needs you to shine bright, so everything that is lurking in the shadows can come to the surface and dissipate.

I'll keep empowering my clients as much as I can. Because I believe that is the road to a better world. Inspiring people to take the reigns of their lives and make heartfelt decisions that are aligned with their true being.

#holisticwellnesscoaching #healing #trauma #triggers #unpopularopinion #wellnessinmind

‚ÄúBut the idea of parental alienation has come under scrutiny in recent years, as women and domestic violence experts have increasingly pointed out that claims of parental alienation often involve cases that stem from domestic abuse resulting in the allegedly abused parent being naturally resistant to allowing the abusive ex-partner to continue parenting the child. Divorced women are claiming they are encouraged by attorneys not to mention domestic violence in their court proceedings for fear of a claim of parental alienation being used against them in custody proceedings.

Studies have shown that when a claim of parental alienation is made, courts increasingly side with the alienated party and often reverse custody orders, returning children to an abusive parent. A 2023 report to the United Nations, labeled parental alienation a ‚Äúpseudo-concept‚Äù that endangers the lives of women and children. The idea of parental alienation as a psychological disorder has also come under heavy scrutiny by other psychologists.‚Äù

My name is #PatriciaDouglas

"The Patricia Douglas case is probably the biggest, best-suppressed scandal in Hollywood history." Vanity Fair.

Take a look at the story that inspired the show and the character of #GirlNextDoor played by @yorkshirewade

Trigger Warning: Themes of sexual assault.

On the evening of May 5, 1937, a 20-year-old Patricia Douglas was brought to work at an MGM party, under the guise of a casting call, with more than 120 other young women.

Herded into a large banquet hall, they were ordered to sit at tables and wait. Studio bosses, assorted MGM bigwigs, male stars, and almost 300 revved-up conventioneers appeared.

Given that they had been promised a stag affair, the salesmen‚Äôs lust-at-first-sight response to a bevy of young, over-made-up beauties makes sad and terrible sense. Delegates mistook the girls for party favors and treated them accordingly; without telephones or transportation, the young women had no means of escape. Tricked into attendance, then trapped into service, they were left to fend for themselves.

Patricia Douglas was one of the first people to come forward after experiencing sexual assault in the film industry, leading to a massive scandal that MGM minimized by a smear campaign. In what was a legal first Patricia Douglas was the first female plaintiff to make rape a federal case based on her civil rights.

Thirty something Vanessa Wye is working a dead end job as a hotel concierge. Dealing with the loss of her father and the slow decline of her once bright academic future, she has sunk into a cycle of alcohol and drugs, just barely managing to keep her head above water. 

At the height of #MeToo, her high school teacher, Jacob Strane, is accused of sexually abusing several girls. This brings back long buried memories of Vanessa‚Äôs own troubled relationship with Strane. 
.

ü•Ä The two timelines - one by a jaded adult Vanessa and the other by the optimistic 15 year old who has a crush on 42 year old English teacher - make for a brilliant and poignant contrast.

ü•Ä I loved Vanessa‚Äôs character progression from a flirty teen to an abused, brainwashed young woman and then to an adult whose life is shaped (and destroyed) by that abuse. I found adult Vanessa‚Äôs weird obsessive love/hate relationship with Strane very interesting.

ü•Ä Strane is obviously despicable and manipulative, but looking at him from Vanessa‚Äôs POV still manages to muddy the lens you view him through. This is a testament to how well Vanessa is written. 

ü•Ä I won‚Äôt lie. This book was deeply disturbing and difficult to read.

.

#FromTheArchive | It was January 2019, the time around which an international movement called #MeToo was gaining prominence in India. #MeToo was a soc¬≠ial-media-driven campaign that started in 2017, when women across the globe started speaking up against sexual harassment, insp¬≠i¬≠red by American activist and rape survivor Tar¬≠ana Burke. In India, #MeToo began with all¬≠e¬≠gations by and against Bollywood celebrit¬≠ies, and gathered steam on social media. As a result, small towns and rural India remained blissfully unaware.

But for many women, it is not easy to speak up, especially in rural areas where conservative and regressive mores automatically tend to put the blame on women who speak up.

Mayank Jain Parichha writes.

Even in healthy relationships without abuse, communication can be difficult and we may escalate conflict by not using the best communication skills. When someone else‚Äôs actions evoke an upsetting emotional response within us, how can we communicate this?

A common communication error is when we use an accusatory or blame statement. In these statements, we say something such as, ‚ÄúYou don‚Äôt care about me,‚Äù or ‚ÄúYou‚Äôre mad at me right now.‚Äù When we say these statements, we are telling the other person what their intentions or feelings are, when in reality, what we are trying to communicate is what emotions come up for us when something happens.

Try the ‚ÄúI feel‚Ä¶ when you‚Ä¶ I wish‚Ä¶ because‚Äù sentence structure. By using this structure, we address our feelings and don‚Äôt make the other person responsible for them. We also explain what about it evoked this emotional response and how you both can navigate the issue in the future.

Remember: emotions just are. No one is to blame for them, not ourselves nor our partner. While we may not have full control over what emotions we experience, we have control over how we respond to them. Additionally, please keep in mind that this communication strategy does not apply in abusive relationships. If you feel like your relationship is abusive, please contact the Domestic Violence Hotline at:

800-799-7233

DESCRIPTION:
Love bombing is a manipulation tactic for control, used in abusive relationships and by those with insecure attachment seeking power. It is when, primarily at the beginning of a relationship, your partner ‚Äúbombs‚Äù you with extreme displays of affection and attention in order to manipulate you.

We often hear about the ‚Äúhoneymoon phase‚Äù in relationships where, typically at the beginning of the relationship, partners are more affectionate and give more focus to the relationship than normal. How do we know the difference? 

In love bombing, it‚Äôs a cycle. They start by showering you with affection, but quickly switch to denying you love and attention as a way to manipulate you into doing things to get that attention back. In the honeymoon phase, you will begin to display more normal levels of attention and affection slowly and gradually overtime as the newness of the relationship wears off. Love and affection is not withheld in an attempt to receive something in return.

DESCRIPTION:
In honour of Black History Month, Black Excellence: A Heritage to Celebrate; a Future to Build, SSAIC would like to recognize Mikki Kendall. 

Mikki Kendall is the author of a New York Times bestseller, Hood Feminism: Notes from the Women That a Movement Forgot, as well as many liberating and profound essays published in platforms such as TIME, the New York Times, The Guardian, the Washington Post, Vogue, and many others. 

Kendall has worn many hats in the span of her career but her focus throughout has surrounded topics of feminism, race, diversity and representation. 

In her book, Hood Feminism, Kendal expresses her activism for women of colour by criticizing the feminist movement for being largely "the province of the privileged" and ignoring problems that disproportionately impact communities of color, including poverty, housing, medical care, and racism. 

The book stands as an essential tool for particularly white women to utilize. This book allow's women of privilege a lens into understanding the impacts of intersectionality and its effects. Kendall draws on her own experiences of hunger, violence, and hypersexualization, to shine a light on a movement that chronically fails to address the needs of all but a few women. 

Kendall's book is a fierce and necessary step towards acknowledging intersectionality and abolishing the line between women experiencing it and those that are privileged enough no to, within a movement essential to all. 

To learn more about Mikki Kendal and her works, check out her website at https://mikkikendall.com/ or scroll through her Instagram @karnythia.

It may be the end of #TeenDatingViolenceAwarenessMonth, but that doesn‚Äôt mean that the conversation has to end here. We wanted to take the time today to provide some support to parents.

A common barrier for teens when it comes to reporting dating or sexual violence is that they don‚Äôt feel like they have a safe adult to disclose to. They may fear that their parents may get too sad hearing what they‚Äôve been through, or may even get angry at them, blame them, or otherwise become aggressive. The first step to prevent further harm is to create a safe space for disclosure.

Parents, even if your child has never shared any experiences like these with you, it‚Äôs important that you are mindful of how you interact with them and these topics in different contexts. Your teen will often think back to your demeanor in other contexts to determine whether or not you are a safe person to disclose to.

Swipe to learn some ways to foster a relationship with your child that demonstrates that you are a safe adult to disclose to before it happens.

We hope to see you for an engaging and inspiring morning at the Betty Griffin Center's First Annual Breakfast on Monday, March 4th, at The Plantation at Ponte Vedra Beach Clubhouse, 220 Plantation Circle.

We'll be hearing from St. Johns County Sheriff Rob Hardwick and survivors and advocates Kristin Paul and Madison Schemitz.

Doors open at 7:00 a.m., with the program starting promptly at 7:30 a.m. Tickets are $75 and may be purchased at https://bit.ly/BGC1stAnnualBreakfast.

Your attendance isn't just about breakfast; it's a testament to your commitment to supporting survivors on their journey to healing and empowerment. Your participation will directly contribute to funding crucial services, such as emergency shelter, counseling, legal support, and preventive education programs

The Betty Griffin Center offers vital emergency and support services, empowering individuals and their families to reclaim their lives with courage and resilience..

For sponsorship opportunities or inquiries, please contact Kenlie Kubart at kenliek@bettygriffincenter.org or (904) 808-8544 x 207.

Ive expereinced child sexual abuse from a sibiling from as early as i can remeber till about 10years old. It isnt always obvious.it isnt always an adult. It isnt always a man. It was just normal, it was my life.  I was again then assaulted by my boyfriend at the time around 12years old. I was then coerced and pressured by my boyfriend at the time around 14 years old.  I was then persued and emotionally manipualted into sexual dynamic by a 23 year old man over the internet at 15 years old.  I was then raped by an lgbt+ peer at 16 years old, i didnt  cognitivly realise i had been raped till a year later. It was my normal, it was my life. I was persued by and had a relationship with a 26 year old man at 17. I was raped by an lgbt+  peer in my early 20s (between 19-22). I dont remeber my age at the time as i was also navigating an emotionally and mentally abusive relationship.
.
.
.
I am not ONLY what has happened to me, this is not ALL that has happened to me. But it is a lot, and it has shaped me. Im glad im safe now, im glad ive done the work to discern safe connection. 
.
.
My story is unfortuntly common. 
.

DESCRIPTION:
In honor of #TeenDatingViolenceAwarenessMonth we‚Äôre answering real questions from real teens who have attended PAVE/Survivors.org presentations.

Today‚Äôs Question üí≠
Is virginity a construct? A personally defined construct?

Virginity is defined as the state of being where one has never had sexual intercourse. The short answer is, yes, virginity is a social construct. Historically, it has been used to shame others, primarily women, and define their worth as a result of their sexual activity. However, not everyone views the concept this way.

Whether or not you choose to personally use the term virginity is completely up to you, making it a self-defined concept. Keep in mind that we should never impose this on others. For those who do choose to use the concept of virginity for themselves, they may experience additional distress if they have been sexually assaulted. This is one reason why it is very important that we understand that sex and sexual assault are not the same thing. If you do use the concept of virginity for yourself, being sexually assaulted does not mean you have lost your virginity. Sexual assault is an act of violence, not sexual intercourse.

DESCRIPTION:
Today, let‚Äôs shed light on a grave issue that affects millions of lives worldwide: Human Trafficking. As we observe National Human Trafficking Awareness Day, it‚Äôs crucial to educate ourselves about this heinous crime and work together to combat it. 

Signs to watch for:

üíú Physical Manifestations: Look out for signs of physical abuse, malnourishment, extreme fatigue, or untreated medical conditions.
 üíú Absence of Autonomy: Individuals may have limited or no access to personal identification documents, money, or personal belongings, indicating a lack of control over their own lives.
 üíú Communication Restrictions: Victims may be prohibited from speaking for themselves or have limited interaction with others. Their communication may be closely monitored or controlled.
 üíú Unconventional Work Situations: Pay attention to individuals who work excessively long hours, reside at their workplace, or display signs of indebtedness to their employer.
üíú Behavioural Clues: Victims may exhibit fearful, anxious, depressed, submissive, tense, or nervous/paranoid behavior. They may also avoid making eye contact.
üíú Inconsistencies in Narratives: Be cautious of individuals who struggle to clarify their current living arrangements or provide inconsistent explanations about how they ended up in their present circumstances.
 üíú Lack of Familiarity with Location or Date: Victims may not know the city they are in, their place of residence, or even the current date.
üíú Suspicious Financial Practices: Pay attention if someone else controls their finances or if they possess unexplained significant debts.

My name is #PatriciaDouglas

"The Patricia Douglas case is probably the biggest, best-suppressed scandal in Hollywood history." Vanity Fair.

Take a look at the story that inspired the show and the character of #GirlNextDoor played by @yorkshirewade 

Trigger Warning: Themes of sexual assault.

On the evening of May 5, 1937, a 20-year-old Patricia Douglas was brought to work at an MGM party, under the guise of a casting call, with more than 120 other young women. 

Herded into a large banquet hall, they were ordered to sit at tables and wait. Studio bosses, assorted MGM bigwigs, male stars, and almost 300 revved-up conventioneers appeared. 

Given that they had been promised a stag affair, the salesmen‚Äôs lust-at-first-sight response to a bevy of young, over-made-up beauties makes sad and terrible sense. Delegates mistook the girls for party favors and treated them accordingly; without telephones or transportation, the young women had no means of escape. Tricked into attendance, then trapped into service, they were left to fend for themselves.

Patricia Douglas was one of the first people to come forward after experiencing sexual assault in the film industry, leading to a massive scandal that MGM minimized by a smear campaign. In what was a legal first Patricia Douglas was the first female plaintiff to make rape a federal case based on her civil rights.

Marie Laura Laliberte

Age 47

Marie Laliberte was 47 when she went missing on New Year's Day in 1997 in Vancouver, B.C. She grew up in Beauval, Saskatchewan. She travelled between Edmonton, Alberta, and Vancouver, and her resource worker at the time reported that she was engaging in a high-risk lifestyle in East Vancouver. She wasn't reported missing until March 8th, 2002 due to the fact that she didn't keep in touch with her family often, and was described to tend towards anti-social behavior.

Marie Lynn Lasas

Age 19

Marie Lynn Lasas was 19 years old and a mother of two children when she went missing. She was walking home on September 21st, 2006, from a friend's place that night. She was reported to have made a stop at her uncle's and then continued on her way home. After that, she disappeared. Nine months later, her body was found behind an abandoned house on the west side of the city where she lived. Police are no longer actively investigating Lasas' death, but the file is still open.

In honor of #TeenDatingViolenceAwarenessMonth we‚Äôre answering real questions from real teens who have attended PAVE/Survivors.org presentations.

Today‚Äôs Question üí≠
If consent is given for something specific, but something else happens under that ‚Äúpermission,‚Äù what should you do in the moment?

One of our pillars of consent is the concept that consent is ongoing throughout the entire interaction, such as before engaging in a different sexual act, and consenting to one specific thing does not mean you consent to another.

When it comes to responding in the moment, there is no ‚Äúshould.‚Äù Our bodies are hardwired to respond to fear, and we generally have little to no control over how our body chooses to respond. No matter what you do in the moment, it‚Äôs not your fault.
If something happens to you, or has happened to you that you did not consent to, and you would like support from PAVE, please reach out to our Director of Survivor Support:
(survivorsupport@pavingtheway.net)
or check out survivors.org for information and resources.

üé§D√©noncer, c‚Äôest aussi ne pas √™tre cru

Les femmes ayant subi des violences conjugales, qu‚Äôelles soient physiques, psychologiques ou sexuelles, ne sont pas toujours crues.

Des personnes peuvent remettre en cause leur parole, qu‚Äôelle fasse partie de leur propre entourage ou de l‚Äôentourage de l‚Äôagresseur.

Mon conseil est le suivant, c‚Äôest ok de ne pas √™tre cru par tout le monde, c‚Äôest scandaleux, c‚Äôest vrai, mais c‚Äôest ok.

Impossible de convaincre tout le monde sur la v√©racit√© de votre parole, inutile de gaspiller votre √©nergie en tentant en vain de convaincre ces personnes. Inutile de vous d√©fendre dans le vide, ou de chercher √† prouver que vous ne mentez pas, que vous avez raison.

Si ces personnes ne vous soutiennent pas, cela en dit long sur l‚Äôint√©r√™t qu‚Äôelles vous portent. Elles ont fait le choix de soutenir l‚Äôagresseur, de ne pas vous croire et c‚Äôest ok.

Pour le bien de votre sant√© mentale, laissez les remettre en cause votre parole, LOIN DE VOUS, laissez les raconter toutes sortes d‚Äôhistoires fictives, salir votre r√©putation, mais TR√àS LOIN DE VOUS.

Vous ne pouvez pas contr√¥ler la b√™tise humaine, la m√©chancet√© gratuite, mais vous pouvez vous en √©loignez, en prenant vos distances avec ces personnes, qui vraisemblablement ne veulent absolument pas votre bien.

Cela peut √™tre difficile, mais prenez de la hauteur, toutes les agitations autour de vous ne n√©cessitent pas forc√©ment votre r√©action. Pr√©servez votre paix.

Vous avez heureusement autour de vous des personnes qui vous croient, des personnes qui vous aiment sinc√®rement et vous soutiennent dans vos d√©marches, concentrez vous sur ces personnes et laisser aller les autres TR√àS LOIN DE VOUS.

‚ú®Unbound - Tarana Burke‚ú® 

üìö one sentence summary
Memoir of the #MeToo Founder #TaranaBurke .

‚ú®Favorite Quote‚ú®
‚Äû‚Ä¶and I wondered how that body that holds so much pain could also hold so much joy.‚Äù Tarana about Maya Angelou

I don‚Äôt know what I expected but I didn‚Äôt expect THIS. Wow. My heart was shattering into million pieces reading about her experiences and the experiences of the other million girls and women she encountered. She deserves all the recognition and respect for all the work she has done and is still doing to this day.

This book gave me a deeper understanding about the creation of the #MeTooMovement and how it all started and why.
Originally it was meant to empower Black and Brown Girls and to encourage them to share their stories and connect with others who endured the same trauma. 
To this day Black women are at a higher risk of sexual assault, as nearly 1 in 5 BW are survivors of rape (www.nbwji.com) 

The topics are heavy but it needs to be talked about. 
If you enjoy #Memoirs I would highly recommend to put this one on your list. Please make sure to check all the #TriggerWarnings .

Anna tells her story of teen dating violence when, as a freshman, she was ‚Äúinstantly hooked‚Äù by a varsity athlete who made her feel great‚Äîuntil he didn‚Äôt. Read Anna‚Äôs story via our highlights or linktree. 

Looking back on her traumatic experience, Anna @feelinghealingenhanced wants others to recognize the warning signs of teen dating and how to get help. She recommends the @sashclubs ‚ÄúTeen Dating Violence‚Äù Power Topic presentation, via our Power Topics highlight or linktree. 

Anna, like many survivors of abuse by male athletes, found it pointless to report because the school ignored victims. If Anna‚Äôs school had taken the proper steps to support reporting students, she could have avoided years of trauma. Schools must create a safe environment for all students, take reports compassionately, and act quickly to stop the harassment. 

Check out SASH Club's Additional Activities page to improve the climate at school or visit @ssaisorg.

2b has a long history of presenting Hannah Moscovitch's new works. 'The Russian Play & Mexico City' in 2008/2010, 'East of Berlin' in 2009/2011, 'What a Young Wife Ought To Know' in 2015/17/18, and of course - 'Old Stock: A Refugee Love Story'. Which opened in 2017 and has been touring the world ever since. 

We are thrilled to be presenting Hannah's work once more, with the world premiere of her latest work, 'Red Like Fruit'. A searing interrogation of the many contradictions and complexities of complicity, consent, patriarchy and traumatic memory in the post #MeToo era.

Over in America, there has been increasing hateful legislation against transgender people proposed and implemented. Such legislation enables and perpetuates hate crimes, including those against children. 

Earlier this month, Nex Benedict, a 16 year old non-binary student and member of the Choctaw nation was brutally attacked in the bathroom at school by their classmates, who had been bullying them for their gender identity. The school didn‚Äôt call an ambulance or report the incident to police, and suspended Nex. They died the next day.

Trans people around the world face dangerous transphobia. They face high rates of abuse and assault, and higher barriers to support. This is not just an American problem; it is also the case here in Australia. 

Children deserve safety. Trans people deserve safety.

‚Äú How much was I expected to take, to absorb and ignore, while they yelled and clicked their tongues, so freely, with no fear of being confronted. Was I stubborn for wanting to walk, was I asking too much?‚Äù

The #MeToo movement has put sexual harassment in the spotlight, but it is definitely not a new occurrence.

In a nationwide study conducted by the UC San Diego Center on Gender Equity and Health, 81% of women reported experiencing some form of sexual harassment and/or assault in their lifetime. 38% of these women reported the offenses happening in their workplace or school.

Being the victim of sexual harassment in the workplace can have a devastating impact mentally and emotionally on a person. No one should have to face the burdens of workplace harassment alone.

If you feel you have been harassed or mistreated in the workplace, call me today to set up a case evaluation at 423-406-1151.

Relationships aren't set in stone, they can shift and evolve over time. While healthy relationships can bring us closer, unhealthy ones may start to exhibit concerning behaviours such as threats, control, or even physical aggression.

Book 5 of 2024: Last year I read (and loved) ‚ÄúThe Husbands‚Äù by Chandler Baker, and after that I added this book to my TBR. This book is ‚ÄúBig Little Lies‚Äù plus the #MeToo movement. A group of women in an office with their secrets, a spreadsheet of sexual offenders, mothers working full-time jobs and raising kids. The last element was common from The Husbands and I am a fan of how Chandler Baker describes the experience in such a universal language. 
I am not too fond of non-linear storytelling generally, and this book relies on that a lot to keep the secrecy about certain events. Blame it on my worldliness or the predictability of the story, I was able to figure out the ‚Äúsecrets‚Äù before these unraveled on the pages. This is not to say that I did not enjoy the book. 
The story seemed very regular to me, but it deserves telling because I am sure this is only a woman‚Äôs experience. There are still people (read: men AND women) who refuse to believe women when they are sexually harassed. In fact, this book shows the mental dilemma of one of the central characters when one of her work friends expects her support against a senior, while she is debating why she was never harassed at work. 
The book has universal truth bombs about harassment at work across departments, socio-economic strata, and industries. The female friendships, seemingly unconditional, are not all rosy in this book. These are real, imperfect women with betrayals, jealousies, and other myriad human emotions towards other women. 
Overall, an entertaining book which kept me invested in the imperfect characters and their pursuits.

A recent lawsuit has been filed against Disney by an employee, identified as Jane Doe, after the company concealed sexual misconduct by former executive Nolan Gonzales, and retaliated against her with a demotion.

She revealed that management repeatedly ignored complaints about Gonzales, allowing him to harass women without consequences due to his revenue-generating role. The lawsuit states that Gonzales assaulted Jane Doe multiple times in 2017 using drugs and coercion, with threats to release intimate videos if she resisted. 

Despite previous complaints, Gonzales reportedly stepped down in 2022 only after additional harassment reports surfaced. 

This lawsuit emphasizes the critical need for large corporations and studios to prioritize employee protection, and the importance of implementing robust policies to address complaints promptly and impartially. Today, and always, we stand with Jane Doe, survivors of Nolan Gonzales, and with all survivors and Silence Breakers.

Today I was the bravest i‚Äôve been in a long time ü§ç

Today I told my mam about what happened to me as a child, as a teenager and as a young adult at the hands of different perpetrators 

My brain told me she was going to respond with blame, shame, anger and disappointment. It turned out that I was actually just projecting those emotions onto her because thats how I sometimes feel within myself ü§ç

She responded with love, acceptance and said she was proud of me ü•∫ she told me I was brave, that she understood and that none of those events were my fault. She told me she was glad I told her if it meant part of my healing. She said she was happy I told her and gave me a big cuddle. She told me she believed me

I feel like this is one of the biggest steps i‚Äôve taken yet and after 17 years of continuous silence, i‚Äôve finally been able to come clean ü§ç

We talked then about my mental health through the years that she lived through with me. My anorexia diagnosis as a teen, the two years of self harm and suicidal tendencies that came in my late teens and my most recent CPTSD diagnosis. She told me she loved me and that she‚Äôs proud of how far I have come despite the trauma ü§ç

The validation i‚Äôve wanted for so long, but been so scared to seek outü§ç so glad I was brave today ü§ç

So pleased to share that I've recently been approved as an Approved Counsellor for victims of crime under the Victims Services Approved Counselling Service (ACS) in NSW. 

This scheme gives approved clients up to 22 hours of free sessions for counselling related to the psychological injuries sustained as a result of their experience of crime. 

My specialties relate to victims and survivors of:
adult survivors of child seggsual abuse
recent seggsual assault 
young people (16-21) 
members of the LGBTIQ+ community 

To see if you're eligible for the scheme head to: https://victimsservices.justice.nsw.gov.au/victims-services/how-can-we-help-you/victims-support-scheme/eligibility-criteria.html

To find my profile link under the scheme head to: https://victimsservices.justice.nsw.gov.au/victims-services/how-can-we-help-you/victims-support-scheme/counselling.html#Find4 

Delighted that I'm now able to offer access to this kind of support with less financial barriers.

Uploaded in April 2019 ‚Äî in the aftermath of a MeToo movement that had gripped the country ‚Äî her post was a detailed account of her sexual abuse by her private tutor, Sunil Dua, over a few months between October 2013 and February 2014. She was in class 7 then and was 13 years old.

It was her post that alerted her parents to what she had gone through. 

Talking to ThePrint, her father now recalls that as soon as he read her post, they decided to file a complaint against Dua. 

‚ÄúWe did not allow any time to lapse after her post. There was no time spent in any discussions,‚Äù he said. The FIR was filed on 14 April 2019, and thus, the trial began.

During the hearing, the father also read out a statement to the court. ‚ÄúIf a paedophile is hidden, he can damage so many lives. I told the judge that a paedophile is like a serial killer. He (Dua) was a loner, never got married and he never revealed his address,‚Äù he told ThePrint.

Anna tells her story of teen dating violence when, as a freshman, she was ‚Äúinstantly hooked‚Äù by a varsity athlete who made her feel great‚Äîuntil he didn‚Äôt. Read Anna‚Äôs story via our highlights or linktree. 

Looking back on her traumatic experience, Anna wants others to recognize the warning signs of teen dating and how to get help. She recommends the @sashclubs ‚ÄúTeen Dating Violence‚Äù Power Topic presentation, via our Power Topics highlight or linktree. 

Anna @feelinghealingenhanced, like many survivors of abuse by male athletes, found it pointless to report because the school ignored victims. If Anna‚Äôs school had taken the proper steps to support reporting students, she could have avoided years of trauma. Schools must create a safe environment for all students, take reports compassionately, and act quickly to stop the harassment. Too often schools don‚Äôt--so students are denied their right to an education free from sexual harassment as guaranteed by Title IX, a federal civil rights law. 

Use @ssaisorg toolkits (in our highlights) to ensure your school is taking the required steps to protect students.

Disability & Sexualized Violence:
People living with disabilities, both mental and physical, self-report having experienced sexualized violence at alarming rates. The exact numbers are difficult to determine, as this intersection is often not studied or researched. Educating those living with disabilities about consent and violence is equally (if not more?) important, as well as the folks that support them. Learn more about this particular intersection, and strategies for educating youth and young adults about consent and violence, in this lunch-n-learn webinar.

I Like to Watch by Emily Nussbaum. This collection of Pulitzer Prize‚Äìwinning Nussbaum‚Äôs favourite columns she‚Äôs written over the years is every TV lover‚Äôs dream. Beginning with how Buffy the Vampire Slayer turned her into a TV critic and then running through columns about The Sopranos, Girls, Adventure Time, Unbreakable Kimmy Schmidt, LOST, Hannibal, black-ish, and soooo many more, it‚Äôs a romp through the last 20 or so years of television. Occasionally you‚Äôll reach a story where there‚Äôs a wee bit of a cringe factor due to stories that wouldn‚Äôt come out until later‚ÄîJoss Whedon is still a geek god, for instance‚Äîand despite the actual book being published after most of those stories had broken, I appreciated her just leaving them within the context of their own time. Nussbaum has always been a brilliant TV critic, and it‚Äôs rather refreshing to go back to a time that‚Äôs, well, not now. Sometimes she‚Äôll drop little things into the middle of an interview that had me laughing out loud‚Äîmy absolute favourite was the blink-and-you‚Äôd-miss-it nugget that Jenji Kohan, the creator of Orange Is the New Black and GLOW, has a pitbull named Gail Feldman‚Ä¶ which made my husband and I LOL and decide we‚Äôre naming our future cats Morty Sherman, Devorah Goldberg, and Judy Feinstein. But the heart of this book is a remarkable essay that lands smack in the middle of it, one that she wrote specifically for the book, called ‚ÄúConfessions of the Human Shield.‚Äù In it she addresses the very thing I mentioned above: that sometimes people do bad things, and the wrong people‚Äîoften fans or TV critics‚Äîget caught in the crossfire for ever having liked them in the first place, something all of us have felt as fans at one point or another, especially in the past 20 years. This 50-page essay addresses specifically the #MeToo movement and Harvey Weinstein accusations, and how the two caused a tsunami that would spiral through what she did for a living‚Äîin all the best and worst ways. It‚Äôs jaw-droppingly good, and if you only read one part of this book, make it that essay. But I hope you read the entire book, which is an amazing look back at the TV shows we love, and why. #bookstagram

DESCRIPTION:
"This intersection of women, violence, and purity has resulted in more than victim blaming and the idolization of predators like GGW - the purity myth is significantly changing the cultural and political landscape as it relates to violence and women. Women have always been blamed for sexual violence done to them; that's nothing new. But in an allegedly post-feminist world, where rape and domestic violence are supposed to be universally reviled, arguments that overtly (or stealthily) blame women, or dismiss violence against them, have that much more power. Because who in this day and age would say that rape is a good thing? Or that a woman just got what was coming to her? No one; instead, today's rape apologism comes wrapped in the rhetoric of equality - That's what makes it different, and so dangerous.

In a 2008 Los Angeles Times article, for example, reporter Heather Mac Donald wrote that there simply is no rape problem on college campuses. In response to a Harvard woman's story about being raped while she was drunk, Mac Donald's wrote that to hold her 'without responsibility requires stripping women of volition and moral agency.'...

This insidious argument about 'responsibility' is having an acute effect on the way all women talk about rape. The very notion of what rape is is being debated - and not in a progressive or useful way....

Of course, many women don't call their assaults rape, for myriad reasons - perhaps because of the shame and stigma attached to sexual assault, or maybe they shy away from the word because they don't want to admit something so awful happen to them. But whatever the reason, it doesn't change the reality of what happened - It doesn't change the fact that someone raped them.

As dangerous as Sessions Stepp's claim that there is such a thing as 'gray rape' is her insinuation that some women are too empowered to be victims...Claims like these, and playing with language without regard for women's experiences, have real life consequences."

Tonight the first of the 4 lectures for images and words that I'll hold on "WOMEN ARTISTS, despite everything"
My personal research on valiant women who still don't have their rightful place in history,
a list of official omissions, of unjustified forgetfulness, of fake attributions.
Naming means making one exist, recognizing means giving dignity and a correct vision of the progress of the world. Erasing from history is violence, there is no culture if there is no memory."

The lectures will be in the Council Hall at the Da Peraga Castle of Municipality of Vigonza, 8.30 pm
- Wednesday 28 February: Visual artists, from the beginning to the threshold of the 20th century
- Thursday 28 March: Visual artists of the 20th and early 2000s
- Wednesday 24 April: Architects and Designers
- Thursday 23 May: Photographers and Filmmakers
Lectures promoted by Veneto Women's Projects Center of Padua, Municipality of Vigonza, in collaboration with the Lottodiognimese association.

7 years ago I was on stage at the Oscars with Lady Gaga and activists and survivors from all of the country! Lady Gaga was nominated for an Oscar for her song that was featured on The Hunting Ground, a powerful documentary about campus sexual violence. 

I am so grateful I got to have this experience. I am so grateful I got to connect with so many fellow survivors of sexual violence. I have made so many lasting friendships from this group and now know so many advocates within this space. I now know so many resources that I wish I had access to as a young survivor‚Äîbut I am also in the position where I have been able to help allot of people through a similar situation. 

If you‚Äôre struggling with the aftermath of sexual violence or harassment, please feel free to reach out to me. I will be happy to connect you with some of the great advocates I know. I believe you. There is a way through. ‚ù§Ô∏è

Also, that amazing tattoo was designed by my incredible friend @jacquelinetlin 
Jackie is one of the most incredibly talented people I have ever met! Her tattoo design, the fire rose unity survivor symbol, has become an icon for survivors all over the world.

#Consent is an important and ongoing conversation. As we learn more and continue to grow the types of conversations we have, it's clear that not everyone really has a clear understanding of what consent really is and how to apply it to everyday conversations. Sometimes it's really easy to talk about the idea as an abstract because we can lay out the black and white definitions. Most people can't make the transition to how it should actually apply in real world situations. It's easy for people to get confused and they have a lot of questions. The problem is that a lot of people still aren't seeking the answers. Some of the largest feedback that I've gotten since putting out my book February 1st is that it's making people look at consent in an entirely new way. They are considering things that they never thought about before. It's important we continue to push the boundaries of our thinking and engage in meaningful conversations about consent. Get your own copy and join the conversation. Together we can take the steps to building a consent culture! It's clear that what we've been doing so far isn't working, we need to try something different. Don't wait to start!
___________________________________________________
Pick up your copy
https://www.exploresextalk.com/product/got-consent/?utm_source=instagram

Ok, now for the full caption‚Ä¶ it‚Äôs long‚Ä¶ you have been warned üòâ‚Ä®‚Ä®As International Women‚Äôs Day approaches and I think about the many incredible women in my life‚Äîwho in spite of their own difficulties, still make space to comfort, encourage, and challenge me on a daily basis‚Äîit would be crazy not to pause to celebrate them.‚Ä®
Looking back, the past year or so feels like it could contain a decade‚Äôs worth of hardships. So many heart-wrenching losses it‚Äôs hard to keep track of them all‚Äîlosing my employment and financial stability to a layoff, my relationship and business partner to a breakup, my reproductive rights and healthcare access to a broken system of governing, my physical autonomy to an industry peer I trusted, and worst of all‚Äîlosing my ride-or-die companion and best friend of 12-years to cancer. I didn‚Äôt think I would survive.‚Ä®‚Ä®But throughout it all, I was never alone. My sisterhood (by blood and by bond) came through like a force of nature, providing the resilience and strength I needed to navigate my darkest days. They were right there beside me, from carrying me through the losses, to celebrating the triumphs with me as I played my first festival and international gigs, released my first EP, and launched my own party series‚Äîtheir unwavering presence and love were my support system every step of the way. ‚Ä®
As 2024 unfolds, I feel at ease knowing that the foundation of my journey is woven with threads of resilience and perseverance by the strong women who came before me and will carry on after me. Here‚Äôs to the women who inspire and empower me every day. ‚Ä®

Tarana Burke, @taranajaneen, founder of the #MeTooMovement, is an African American civil rights activist known for her work in advocating for survivors of sexual violence, particularly within marginalized communities, including women of color, LGBTQ+ individuals, and low-income individuals.

Burke first coined the phrase "Me Too" in 2006 as a way to empower and support survivors of sexual assault, particularly young women of color. Her intention was to create a sense of solidarity and understanding among survivors.

She is the author of Unbound: My Story of Liberation and the Birth of the Me Too Movement, and You Are Your Best Thing: Vulnerability, Shame Resilience, and the Black Experience. Her letter to her great grandmother is included in the book, Black Love Letters, a collection of essays on community, joy, resilience and more.

DESCRIPTION:
My story - Part 1 üôèüíóüí™

If I'm honest I don't know where to begin, I've been in the the dark for a while facing and healing my past .

I was sexually abused as a child and came from an abusive family.
I was neglected , abandoned and I have pretty much been on my own my whole life.
I left home at 16 and left the UK at 17 .

I ran away from my past and have hidden this from the world and even myself. 
I had not gone through the pain, grief and anger to heal.

Therefore keeping everything inside I created a false self a people pleaser.

A people pleaser to keep the peace, to be loved and liked. To pretend everything was ok to people so that I would be accepted.

When I did have the courage to tell people my story it was too much I was a "Victim" and even told I was too dramatic , sensitive or that I thought the world was against me.

I understand that it's not easy for people to hear these things and it makes them uncomfortable , this is not really something we talk about in our society!!
They don't do it with a bad intention, they are not therapists and also when they are avoident how can they have empathy and feel for you if they don't themselves. 
I also get this as I did it my self too I've always been sensitive and have felt the sadness but I never really acknowledged what really happened I did my best not to get in a hole.

Not acknowledgeing the pain,  anger and grief I had inside I just continued surviving creating coping mechanisms to keep going and of course at one point it all came too much for me so I had to go deep inside.

Once I stopped having an eating disorder, stopped drinking and smoking and getting rid of all my distractions I started to heal.

Yoga has been a big anchor for for me.
A tool to ground and accept the process and to connect spiritually.

But it wasn't until COVID and that my daughter came in my life that I was ready to face the sexual abuse.

Are you looking to boost your cause on social media? Share your passion by telling your story! How about the story that inspired your passion? From the days of sitting around a crackling fire and telling your family and friends stories that turned into legends, time has proven that the best way to connect with people is through telling them a story.

In this short-attention-span era it's important to capture your audience's attention immediately or they will move on. I know I do! The best way to do this is with visuals to capture attention - videos/reels are an excellent method to use. Try keeping it fresh with a variety of different types of posts to keep people interested and provide them with something they want to keep coming back to see. 

And did you know this year is all about being REAL? Be real, talk to your audience, interact with your supporters, ask questions, and build a community! When people feel involved and you share your raw passion, it is much easier to ignite a fire. üî•

Need help coming up with a strategy? Need someone to create some posts for you? Need a logo for your cause? Just slide into my DMs and let's connect!

Narcissists demonstrate a profound lack of empathy, unable to genuinely understand or validate the emotions and experiences of others. 

They view individuals as mere instruments for their gratification, treating them as objects to be used and discarded at will. 

This callous disregard for the feelings and needs of others is a fundamental aspect of their personality, deeply ingrained and resistant to change. 

It is so important for you to recognise that the narcissist's behaviour is not your fault; it stems from the narcissist's inherent traits and dysfunctional coping mechanisms.

My aunt lived in that area, and we were taken there daily. I can remember her telling me I was special and that I would be a star someday. That I had to do everything she said. Listen, practice.
My father was supposed to be watching my sister and me, but he would take us there and leave us with her. For part of that time we stayed with my aunt until we could get our own place. My father was supposed to be looking for work, but he would take off with my blood uncles every day, so it got to be that I never saw either parent for long periods of time. That would change on occasion when my father would take me with him to bars while he drank or played in a band or both. I would be at the bar with one of his girlfriends. It seemed perfectly natural to me.
My aunt began to sexually abuse me the first night. It continued the entire time we were there. Months. I didn't know until years later that my sister was locked in a closet while this went on.
Eventually we got a place of our own and the abuse stopped.
A few months later my cousins came to live with us and the sexual abuse started again. Just different people. It ended a few months later when they were caught. They had us tied up. The cords were tight. Not really cords at all, cloths line. My sister and I were tied back to back. My cousins, a sister and brother had already molested us for over an hour. I cannot recall where my mother was during that period of my life. She was gone a lot. I think she was working because he didn't work. That's all I know.

DESCRIPTION:
Helpful reminder for a Monday. 

You are not your work. 

You are not the you who is late for work, early for work, enjoys your work, or can't wait for work to end. 

You are not what you do, or how you feel. 

What makes up you is a complex beautiful tapestry of experiences, dreams, potential, loves, beliefs, past lives, future lives, friendships, acquaintances, the interaction with the stranger on the train. 

Big milestones, small fancies. 

But the main message here - you are not your work. 

And therefore, do not fear a Monday morning. 

It is just another day, another opportunity to get to know yourself a little bit deeper. 

And, breathe....

DESCRIPTION:
Generous donations from our community have enabled us to renovate another room at our shelter. We very much appreciate your support.

Support of these efforts is both an investment in the only certified emergency shelter for survivors of domestic and sexual abuse in St. Johns County and their minor children and a commitment to help those transition from domestic violence victims to survivors.

Our rooms need renovations and makeovers, and we've asked for makeovers to include paint, bedding, d√©cor, and bathroom supplies. Last year, 325 adults and children spent 28,652 bed nights in our shelter.

Donations to this project will help with the bedroom makeovers and the needed flooring, repairs, hardware, and appliances to create a safe and welcoming environment throughout our shelter. 

With the growth we've seen in St. Johns County, more families need our help than ever before - and the complexity of those needs has also increased. 

If you'd like to help, please call our office at (904) 808-8544 or donate any amount online at the link in our profile, and write room makeover in the comments. 

If you're being abused or have been abused, please call the Betty Griffin Center 24-hour crisis hotline at (904) 824-1555, or TTY users dial (904) 827-0236. Text us at https://bettygriffincenter.org/ by clicking on the blue icon.

üö®NEW EPISODEüö®

Chloe Wade on Writing for Theatre and her new play As SHE Likes It

Chloe is an actor, writer and theatre maker who trained at the International School of Acting and Central School of Speech and Drama. 

With over 10 years of working in film, TV and theatre she is best known for playing Joanne Grantham in BBC‚Äôs Doctors and the lead role in independent film Honeycomb Lodge that won the Best Film at the Delhi International Film Festival. Over lockdown she starred alongside Helen Mirren in The Secret Life of Ophelia. 

She is also the alumna of the Actor-Writer course and is a supported writer of the Sheffield Theatre‚Äôs Bank Cohort. Chloe is currently reigning champion of the Birmingham Rep‚Äôs Monologue Slam competition with her piece ‚ÄúMay I Take Your Order Please‚Äù, based on her time working in hospitality. 

In this episode we discuss Chloe‚Äôs brand new play that‚Äôs currently on tour across the UK, As SHE Likes It, a play bringing to light the sexual harassment that has/is going on in Hollywood and how it dates back back to the 1920s, not just to Harvey Weinstein. 

The play is based on the story of actress Patricia Douglas who was abused at an MGM party in 1937. Despite her efforts to bring her perpetrators to justice the case was thrown out and nothing came of it. I had the privilege to see and review the show with @uppercircle_theatre (review group that Chloe and I are part of) you can find it on my profile. It‚Äôs a fantastic piece packed with harsh truths that everyone needs to hear and see to stop this harassment from continuing. 

Check out Chloe‚Äôs website and Instagram for more information on her, the tour and how to get in touch. 

Website: chloe-wade.com
Instagram: @chloewadprod @yorkshirewade

My number one take away from the course:
if you bring up a difficult conversation and another shuts it down, it‚Äôs their job to return to the conversation.  If they don‚Äôt, rinse and repeat a few times before letting them go so you don‚Äôt continue having one sided conversations without resolution.  If you shut it down, let them know when you‚Äôll return to work on resolution. When people show you who they are, believe them.  Actions over words though words are telling. üôåüèªüòâüôèüèº

#metoo began with women and cascaded through many different professions.
Let's be clear, it is not a question of profession, but a societal structural one.

Any abused child who could not be witnessed and trusted in their pain remains stuck with loneliness, hurt, fear, shame ‚Ä¶within the adult who is carrying them
The gender of the child does not matter, the pain is similar.
What changes is the perception of 
what is a woman: kind, gentle, patient, smiling, sweet, weak, emotional, a mother or a whore 
and what is a man: strong, powerful, a leader, does not show emotions, solid, a knight, a warrior
well, no.
all of those traits can belong to a man or a woman
Working with an adult is working with kids and teens

As Australia reels in the wake of another domestic violence related homicide, we really need to address how we talk about these issues. 

We immediately had the press sensationalising the murder, reframing and focusing on it as the outcome of a ‚Äúlove triangle‚Äù, a scandal to be gossiped about rather than taken seriously. 

We then had the Police Commissioner calling it a ‚Äúcrime of passion‚Äù. Murders perceived as crimes of passion get taken less seriously by courts, as well as the media (as we have already seen). It also overlooks the power dynamics involved with the alleged murder being a police officer who used a police-issued firearm as the murder weapon. Australia has long had a very serious problem with police officers failing to take action against other police officers accused of domestic violence. 

There is then also the issue of domestic violence being taken less seriously in the context of LGBT relationships. LGBT victim-survivors face far more barriers to support and justice.

We can‚Äôt keep excusing, enabling, and protecting abusers. 

Luke Davies and Jesse Baird should still be alive, enjoying their lives together, enjoying the love they had for each other, enjoying the Sydney Mardi Gras with the LGBTQ community.

Spivak hablaba de ese espacio en blanco entre las palabras que, si bien no tiene sonido, tiene entidad y existe, aunque permanezca en silencio. De la misma forma, estas manos interpretan un mensaje que es global, que se hizo viral en 2017 con un #MeToo y un #TimesUp pero que sigue vigente con un #SeAcab√≥ que es tambi√©n internacional. Un grito concentrado en unas manos precisas.

.

Some hands interpret, in sign language, the words "It's over"; Spivak said that subaltern subjects could not speak not because of their physical incapacity (which they did have) but because of their status on the margin, without the capacity to enunciate or name themselves. Spivak spoke of that blank space between words that, although it has no sound, has an entity and exists, even if it remains silent. In the same way, these hands interpret a message that is global, that went viral in 2017 with a #MeToo and a #TimesUp but that remains valid with a #SeAcab√≥ that is also international. A cry concentrated in precise hands.

Authored By: Simran
The PoSH Act was put into effect to shield women from sexual harassment at work and to prevent it from happening, providing a safe atmosphere for them to work in. As a mandatory compliance with the PoSH Act, any organization with more than ten employees must set up an Internal Complaints Committee (ICC) in the prescribed manner to receive and handle women's complaints of sexual harassment in a highly confidential and time-bound manner. The POSH Act is not gender-neutral; only women can register complaints.

Today, I want to take a moment to shed light on a topic that‚Äôs incredibly important yet often silenced: healing from sexual trauma.

Sexual trauma can leave deep scars on our hearts and minds, impacting every aspect of our lives. 

But I want you to know that healing is possible. It‚Äôs a journey that takes time, courage, and support, but it is within reach.

If you‚Äôre struggling with the aftermath of sexual trauma, please know that you are not alone. 

There are resources and communities out there ready to offer guidance, understanding, and a safe space to heal.

Remember, your experiences do not define you. 

You are resilient, worthy of love, and deserving of peace. 

It‚Äôs okay to seek help and to take care of yourself along the way.

Let‚Äôs break the silence, support one another, and walk hand in hand on the path to healing.
